Let $h_1,$ $h_2,$ and $h_3$ be the lengths of the altitudes from $D$ to $\overline{AB},$ $\overline{AC},$ and $\overline{BC},$ respectively.  Then the areas of triangles $ABD,$ $ACD,$ and $BCD$ are $\frac{1}{2} h_1,$ $\frac{1}{2} h_2,$ and $\frac{1}{2} h_3,$ respectively.  Therefore, we want $h_1 = h_2 = h_3.$

Let $H$ be the orthocenter of triangle $ABC.$  Then $\overline{DH}$ is perpendicular to $\overline{BC},$ so $h_3 = DH.$  Also, $AH$ is perpendicular to $\overline{BC},$ so $h_2 = AH \sin A.$  Similarly, $h_1 = BH \sin B.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, H, P, Q;

A = (5,8);
B = (3,-2);
C = (6,1);
D = (4.25,3);
H = extension(A, foot(B,A,C), B, foot(A,B,C));
P = extension(D, D + (C - B), A, B);
Q = extension(D, D + (B - C), A, C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--H);
draw(B--H);
draw(C--H);
draw(D--P);
draw(D--Q);
draw(B--foot(B,A,C));
draw(A--foot(A,B,C));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NE);
label("$H$", H, S);
label("$P$", P, S);
label("$Q$", Q, E, UnFill);
[/asy]

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\cos A = \frac{BC^2 + AC^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot BC \cdot AC} = \frac{7}{\sqrt{74}}.\]Then by the Law of Sines,
\[AH = \frac{BC}{\cos A} = \frac{5 \sqrt{74}}{7}.\]Also, $\sin A = \frac{8}{\sqrt{74}},$ so
\[h_2 = AH \sin A = \frac{40}{7}.\]Let $E$ be the foot of the altitude from $H$ to $\overline{BC}.$  Then $BE = 3,$ $CE = 2,$ and $HE = \frac{40}{7}.$  By the Pythagorean Theorem, $BH = \sqrt{BE^2 - HE^2} = \frac{\sqrt{209}}{7},$ so
\[h_1 = BH \sin B = \frac{16}{\sqrt{209}}.\]Finally, $DH = h_3 = h_2 = \frac{40}{7},$ so $D$ lies on the line through $H$ parallel to $\overline{BC}.$  This line has equation
\[y = -\frac{1}{3} x + \frac{20}{3}.\]Since $D$ is inside triangle $ABC,$ we must have $P$ and $Q$ inside triangle $ABC$ as well.  Hence, $P$ and $Q$ must both lie above the line $y = -\frac{1}{3} x + \frac{20}{3}.$

[asy]
